## GitLab Flow vs Other Strategies

| Feature | GitLab Flow | GitHub Flow | Git Flow |
|---------|-------------|------------|----------|
| Environment Branches | ✅ Yes | ❌ No | ❌ No |
| Merge Requests | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes |
| Release Branches | ✅ Yes | ❌ No | ✅ Yes |
| Staging Environment | ✅ Yes | ⚠️ Optional | ⚠️ Optional |
| Multiple Versions | ✅ Yes | ❌ No | ✅ Yes |

## Git Commands

```bash
# Create feature branch
git checkout -b feature/new-feature

# Push and create merge request
git push origin feature/new-feature

# Merge to main (via GitLab UI)
# Auto-deploys to staging

# Promote to production
git checkout production
git merge main
git push origin production
# Auto-deploys to production

# Create release tag
git tag -a v1.0.0 -m "Release version 1.0.0"
git push origin v1.0.0
```

## Best Practices
✅ Keep feature branches short-lived (1-2 days)
✅ Use descriptive merge request titles
✅ Run CI/CD tests automatically
✅ Require approvals before merge
✅ Use environment-specific configurations
✅ Tag releases for version tracking

## When to Use
- Projects needing staging environments
- Teams using GitLab CI/CD
- Multi-environment deployments
- Teams wanting GitHub Flow + versioning
- Applications requiring release management

---
**Ideal for:** GitLab users, staged deployments, release management, and balanced simplicity with version control.
